Ed,<br>
I am very sorry if anything I said offended you.  I respect your Native American views, and I wish to contribute in a forum of healing and true dialog.  Vietnam has always been part of my life, through my father and the Nam vets I voulunteer to help.  I've always respected the Vietnam warrior and have done what I could to aid them and help keep what is a proud image.  I just don't like to be told that I can't speak.  No, I can't speak first hand of the war in Vietnam, but I can speak of the aftermath, the wars fought by veterans and their families day to day.  If I came off a bit emotional, it is just that Vietnam strikes a cord in me.  My generation has not had a horrible war, this is due to the fact that every Vietnam vet and many non-vets who lived through the war have to this day made sure it has not happened again to this point in time, our (my generation) service comes in the form more peaceful jobs and efforts.  Thus, the memories and sorrows of one war have kept this nation from shedding great amounts of blood in some other war.  That is a legacy that even the warriors of World War II couldn't or didn't prevent.  We can and should be strong as a nation, but be smart about our fights.  Ed, your Native American background must show how smart warriors pick their fights wisely.  What made me sick about Vietnam is 58,000 Americans who had no future.  Sure someone must die in war, but why so many?  It is hard for me to see friends of my father who were close to my age when they died, not having a chance to live any more of their life.  Vietnam and its legacy will NEVER go away-it just can't.<br>
Ed, my comments about no place in cyberspace being sacred was in sarcasm about the world today.  I was not attacking your thread. If there is a place where thoughts can be accepted and respected, I would like to be posting there.  Much of the rest of the web is subject to every &quot;dinky dau&quot; poster that comes along.  No more fighting from me, unless it is in defense of Nam vets.<br>
Peace and Welcome Home    
